The Aisha Buhari Foundation, has flagged-off train the trainer workshop for 750 youths on E-learning technique, on how to pass WAEC and NECO exams in Adamawa state. Prof Abba Tahir, at the event in Yola Friday, who  represented the First Lady said, 300 others was trained  in 2017 to raid the state out-of -school children in the state. The beneficiaries were largely affected due to lack of sponsorship and inability to pass certificate entrance  at post secondary school levels. The program under the Future Assured Youths Education and Empowerment Program (FA-YEEP), will support participants with computer tablets for online practical of their registered subjects. “Nigeria is still ranked one of the highest counties with out-for-school children in the world. “Unless we figure out way of addressing causes in education deprivation, we may never be balanced in our development. “The case is more disheartening in the northern states, where insurgency and poverty furthers worsen dilapidated structures. “Education deprivation in Northern Nigerian is driven by economic barrier and socio-socio-cultural norms and practice, that discourage attendance in formal education.” Earlier, Dr Naseer Ajoge, ABF project lead said  the computer tablets  would serve as tools for computer based technical training to enable  beneficiaries assess subject of their choice for practical. Ajoge further noted that, JAMB past questions and simulated laboratories for science  subjects have also been programmed for the beneficiaries. Commissioner for Education and Human Development, represented by Sunday Stephen, reiterated  government readiness to support  the foundation. 